Start removal of web UI config interface

As the configuration implementation writes all default fields regardless
if they are present in file it sort of messes up the structure of the
config file.

The need to update the configuration at runtime is small as I see it.
Combined with the process has to be restarted for the changes to
have an impact it not a very valueable interface.

As the trackers are no longer hardcoded it makes no sense keeping and
maintaining the interface.

Thus it is being removed.

Remove settings web UI interface

The settings view is a lot more static than the tracker settings view.
However, the config implementation still writes all default values to
file which is undesired. The process also has to be restarted to the
changes to take affect.

Add command line flags for config locations

One flag for specifying where the tracker XML configurations are
located.

One flag for specifying the user configuration file. Since specifying
the path requires parsing of input parameters before parsing config the
config cannot be fetched in the global scope of each module. The API to
the config has either been extended to fetch the data when necessary or
the config is given as a parameter.

Because of this it was convenient to also only notify configured
backends.

Decrease db_session scope

Pony is not compatible with async/await statements. More specifically,
when the context manager is active await is not possible. The database
sessions are therefore changed to what's essential even though it may
cause several session per event. Multiple session per event is rare
though, it only happens if a release is snatched. Should be fine.

Move shutdown to signal handler

socketio replaces the werkzeug dev webserver when using eventlet and so
the shutdown endpoint does no longer work. Moving the shutdown to a
signal handler, which makes sense anyway, as it's easy to make graceful
shutdown from CLI.

IRC and db threads as well as backend's session are shutdown and closed
properly. The web thread has no natural flag or event for shutdown that
I can find. There is probably some hacky way to send SystemExit
exception to it but might as well just terminate the program.
